{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1775858317945,"sessionID":"ses_28698f613ffezy8v7A1tWucgIy","part":{"id":"prt_d79677a76001mer8EKnKvfS40Y","messageID":"msg_d796771460013noid3Quq2mmgC","sessionID":"ses_28698f613ffezy8v7A1tWucgIy","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775858319916,"sessionID":"ses_28698f613ffezy8v7A1tWucgIy","part":{"id":"prt_d79677cff001slKxIaQbJ4rOmd","messageID":"msg_d796771460013noid3Quq2mmgC","sessionID":"ses_28698f613ffezy8v7A1tWucgIy","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_03dff82089214615a24c255e","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/changes/AR-015/proposal.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/changes/AR-015/proposal.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Proposal: PicoD Command Execution API (AR-015)\n2: \n3: ## Summary\n4: \n5: Implement the command execution API for the PicoD module in `pkg/picod`, providing secure and controlled command execution capabilities for sandboxed environments.\n6: \n7: ---\n8: \n9: ## Purpose\n10: \n11: The PicoD command execution API provides:\n12: \n13: 1. **Secure Command Execution**: Execute commands within controlled sandbox environments\n14: 2. **Resource Limits**: Enforce CPU, memory, and time limits on command execution\n15: 3. **Output Capture**: Capture stdout, stderr, and exit codes\n16: 4. **Streaming Support**: Optional streaming output for long-running commands\n17: 5. **Cancellation**: Support for command cancellation via context\n18: \n19: This implementation is the focus of AR-015 and builds upon the sandbox infrastructure established in previous ARs.\n20: \n21: ---\n22: \n23: ## Scope\n24: \n25: ### In Scope\n26: \n27: - `pkg/picod/picod.go` - Core PicoD structure and initialization\n28: - `pkg/picod/executor.go` - Command execution logic\n29: - `pkg/picod/limits.go` - Resource limit configuration and enforcement\n30: - `pkg/picod/output.go` - Output capture and streaming\n31: - `pkg/picod/security.go` - Security validations and sandboxing\n32: - Unit tests with mocked executors\n33: - Integration tests with real command execution\n34: \n35: ### Out of Scope\n36: \n37: - Container runtime integration (covered in separate ARs)\n38: - Network namespace manipulation\n39: - Filesystem isolation beyond chroot\n40: - User namespace management\n41: - Distributed command execution\n42: \n43: ---\n44: \n45: ## Impact Analysis\n46: \n47: ### Dependencies\n48: \n49: | Package | Purpose |\n50: |---------|---------|\n51: | `context` | Command cancellation and timeouts |\n52: | `os/exec` | Command execution primitives |\n53: | `syscall` | Process management and signals |\n54: | `k8s.io/klog/v2` | Structured logging |\n55: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/common/types` | SandboxInfo type definitions |\n56: \n57: ### Affected Components\n58: \n59: 1. **Sandbox Manager**: Will use PicoD for command execution within sandboxes\n60: 2. **Workload Manager**: Will invoke PicoD APIs for job execution\n61: 3. **Security Module**: Will configure security policies for command execution\n62: 4. **Monitoring System**: Will collect metrics from command execution\n63: \n64: ### Backward Compatibility\n65: \n66: - This is a new module with no existing API surface\n67: - No breaking changes to existing components\n68: - Configuration via environment variables and programmatic API\n69: \n70: ### Risk Assessment\n71: \n72: | Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n73: |------|------------|--------|------------|\n74: | Command injection | Low | High | Input validation, allowlist-based command selection |\n75: | Resource exhaustion | Medium | High | Enforce strict CPU/memory/time limits |\n76: | Privilege escalation | Low | Critical | Run as non-root, drop capabilities, use namespaces |\n77: | Output buffer overflow | Low | Medium | Stream large outputs, enforce size limits |\n78: | Zombie processes | Medium | Low | Proper process reaping, signal handling |\n79: \n80: ---\n81: \n82: ## Alternatives Considered\n83: \n84: ### Alternative 1: Use Existing Library (e.g., go-execute)\n85: \n86: **Approach**: Leverage existing command execution libraries\n87: \n88: **Pros**:\n89: - Less code to maintain\n90: - Battle-tested implementations\n91: \n92: **Cons**:\n93: - May not meet specific security requirements\n94: - Additional dependency\n95: - Less control over resource limits\n96: \n97: **Decision**: Implement custom solution for full control over security and limits.\n98: \n99: ### Alternative 2: Shell-based Execution\n100: \n101: **Approach**: Execute commands via `/bin/sh -c`\n102: \n103: **Pros**:\n104: - Simple implementation\n105: - Shell features available\n106: \n107: **Cons**:\n108: - Security risks (shell injection)\n109: - Harder to control resource limits\n110: - Additional attack surface\n111: \n112: **Decision**: Use direct execve-style execution for better security.\n113: \n114: ---\n115: \n116: ## Implementation Details\n117: \n118: ### PicoD Structure\n119: \n120: ```go\n121: type PicoD struct {\n122:     sandboxID     string\n123:     workDir       string\n124:     limits        *ResourceLimits\n125:     securityOpts  *SecurityOptions\n126:     logger        klog.Logger\n127: }\n128: ```\n129: \n130: ### Resource Limits\n131: \n132: ```go\n133: type ResourceLimits struct {\n134:     Timeout       time.Duration\n135:     MaxCPU        float64\n136:     MaxMemory     int64\n137:     MaxOutputSize int64\n138:     MaxProcesses  int\n139: }\n140: ```\n141: \n142: ### Security Options\n143: \n144: ```go\n145: type SecurityOptions struct {\n146:     UID           int\n147:     GID           int\n148:     Capabilities  []string\n149:     ReadOnlyFS    bool\n150:     NoNetwork     bool\n151: }\n152: ```\n153: \n154: ### Command Execution API\n155: \n156: ```go\n157: type Command struct {\n158:     Path    string\n159:     Args    []string\n160:     Env     []string\n161:     Dir     string\n162:     Stdin   io.Reader\n163:     Stdout  io.Writer\n164:     Stderr  io.Writer\n165: }\n166: \n167: type CommandResult struct {\n168:     ExitCode   int\n169:     Stdout     []byte\n170:     Stderr     []byte\n171:     Duration   time.Duration\n172:     OOMKilled  bool\n173:     Timeout    bool\n174: }\n175: \n176: func (p *PicoD) Run(ctx context.Context, cmd *Command) (*CommandResult, error)\n177: func (p *PicoD) Start(ctx context.Context, cmd *Command) (*Process, error)\n178: func (p *Process) Wait() (*CommandResult, error)\n179: func (p *Process) Kill(signal os.Signal) error\n180: ```\n181: \n182: ---\n183: \n184: ## Configuration Reference\n185: \n186: ### Environment Variables\n187: \n188: | Variable | Required | Default | Notes |\n189: |----------|----------|---------|-------|\n190: | `PICOD_WORKDIR` | No | `/tmp/picod` | Base working directory |\n191: | `PICOD_DEFAULT_TIMEOUT` | No | `30s` | Default command timeout |\n192: | `PICOD_MAX_MEMORY` | No | `128Mi` | Default memory limit |\n193: | `PICOD_MAX_CPU` | No | `1.0` | Default CPU limit |\n194: \n195: ---\n196: \n197: ## Testing Strategy\n198: \n199: ### Unit Tests\n200: \n201: 1. **TestPicoD_Run_Success**: Basic command execution\n202: 2. **TestPicoD_Run_Timeout**: Command exceeds timeout\n203: 3. **TestPicoD_Run_OOM**: Command exceeds memory limit\n204: 4. **TestPicoD_Run_Cancelled**: Context cancellation\n205: 5. **TestPicoD_OutputCapture**: Stdout/stderr capture\n206: 6. **TestPicoD_SecurityValidation**: Invalid commands rejected\n207: \n208: ### Integration Tests\n209: \n210: 1. **TestPicoD_Integration_FullLifecycle**: Full execution flow\n211: 2. **TestPicoD_Integration_Concurrent**: Multiple concurrent commands\n212: 3. **TestPicoD_Integration_ResourceLimits**: Verify limits are enforced\n213: \n214: ---\n215: \n216: ## Acceptance Criteria\n217: \n218: - [ ] `PicoD` struct implements all required methods\n219: - [ ] Resource limits are enforced (timeout, CPU, memory)\n220: - [ ] Output capture works correctly\n221: - [ ] Cancellation via context is supported\n222: - [ ] Security validations prevent dangerous operations\n223: - [ ] All unit tests pass\n224: - [ ] Integration tests pass\n225: - [ ] Code coverage >= 80%\n226: - [ ] Documentation includes usage examples\n227: \n228: ---\n229: \n230: ## References\n231: \n232: - Sandbox Infrastructure: `changes/AR-012/proposal.md`\n233: - Session Storage: `changes/AR-013/proposal.md`\n234: - Valkey Storage: `changes/AR-014/proposal.md`\n\n(End of file - total 234 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Proposal: PicoD Command Execution API (AR-015)\n\n## Summary\n\nImplement the command execution API for the PicoD module in `pkg/picod`, providing secure and controlled command execution capabilities for sandboxed environments.\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nThe PicoD command execution API provides:\n\n1. **Secure Command Execution**: Execute commands within controlled sandbox environments\n2. **Resource Limits**: Enforce CPU, memory, and time limits on command execution\n3. **Output Capture**: Capture stdout, stderr, and exit codes\n4. **Streaming Support**: Optional streaming output for long-running commands\n5. **Cancellation**: Support for command cancellation via context\n\nThis implementation is the focus of AR-015 and builds upon the sandbox infrastructure established in previous ARs.\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/changes/AR-015/proposal.md","time":{"start":1775858319904,"end":1775858319913}}}}
